verb.description: To distinguish (a thing or group of things) further, especially to subdivide into further categories; to subclassify.

origin: Early 17th century; earliest use found in Edmund Bolton (?1575/5–?1634), antiquary and historian. From sub- + distinguish. Compare post-classical Latin subdistinguere to punctuate, separate by a comma (2nd or 3rd cent., after Byzantine Greek ὑποστίζειν), to separate, distinguish, and also Spanish subdistinguir, Italian suddistinguere.
